              <h2 style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Arduino<br />
                </span></h2>
              <p></p>
              The Arduino is a microcontroller that can easily be programed by a
              computer via the USB port.  It uses a variant of C and has a huge
              following so sample code is easy to come by.  I have used it in my
              rover along with a Raspberry Pi board running Linux.  The Arduino
              comes in many flavors and not all are created equal  as I have
              found out.<br />
              <br />
              My first rover used the Uno that has 14 basic I/O pins some analog
              some digital.  The 6 analog pins have built in A/D converters with
              10bits (0-1024) and also can bu used as pulse width modulation for
              output.  you can hook a verity of devices directly to the Arduino
              including standard hobby servos, switches, sensors and
              potentiometers.  There are also a wide verity of shields that just
              plug into the Ardunio and come with pre built libraries to get you
              off and running fast.<br />
              <br />
              Next I used the Due which has many more I/O pins and found that I
              needed to modify the my hardware to be compatible as the timer
              used for the pulse width modulation for pins 9 and 19 changed form
              an 16bit timer to a 8bit timer.  To fix this I needed to use pins
              11 and 12 that have a 16bit timer. <br />
